You have a really interesting background.

59
00:04:35,040 --> 00:04:37,919
I usually don't spend time on background, but I thought this would be fun.

60
00:04:37,919 --> 00:04:40,400
Uh I was looking at your LinkedIn and your background.

61
00:04:40,400 --> 00:04:44,240
The beginning of your career, you spent 13 years at Pitchfork.

62
00:04:44,240 --> 00:04:44,560
>> Yes.

63
00:04:44,560 --> 00:04:45,680
>> Reviewing music.

64
00:04:45,680 --> 00:04:46,240
Okay.

65
00:04:46,240 --> 00:04:47,520
Reviewing artists.

66
00:04:47,520 --> 00:04:49,360
Pitchfork was like a massive deal.

67
00:04:49,360 --> 00:04:53,280
I don't know where it is today, but it was like the most influential music review site.

68
00:04:53,280 --> 00:04:54,800
Is it still a big deal or is it less?

69
00:04:54,800 --> 00:04:55,680
>> It is still a big deal.

70
00:04:55,680 --> 00:05:06,000
It was okay much less of a big deal when I started working for them and I was a 16-year-old music nerd writing record reviews in my bedroom at my parents apartment.

71
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:06,240
>> Okay.

72
00:05:06,240 --> 00:05:08,400
So, what I'm hearing is you helped make them a big deal.

73
00:05:08,400 --> 00:05:08,800
Excellent.

74
00:05:08,800 --> 00:05:09,600
That's impact.

75
00:05:09,600 --> 00:05:12,320
We're going to talk talk about >> I was better at telling my own story.

76
00:05:12,320 --> 00:05:14,800
That's exactly what I'd be saying before I started.

77
00:05:14,800 --> 00:05:17,199
I was product manager number one at Pitchfork.

78
00:05:17,199 --> 00:05:21,360
>> Funny enough, like you look at your resume, you like went into product management from Pitchfork.

79
00:05:21,360 --> 00:05:22,800
Very typical career path.

80
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:26,960
By the way, if you're on YouTube watching, there's a lot of musical paraphernalia behind you and awesome guitar.

81
00:05:26,960 --> 00:05:30,880
So, clearly there's a a thread of music throughout your background.

82
00:05:30,880 --> 00:05:32,720
Let me ask you this question.

83
00:05:32,720 --> 00:05:39,120
>> What is most similar about making music, critique, and even critiquing music uh and building great product?

84
00:05:39,120 --> 00:05:42,000
>> The magic lies in the way people work together.

85
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:47,680
That's really what I think has been the consistent thread between all the work that I've done.

86
00:05:47,680 --> 00:05:49,360
I I spent years as a touring musician.

87
00:05:49,360 --> 00:05:52,880
I still occasionally tour in my friend Will Chef's band.

88
00:05:52,880 --> 00:06:03,680
And it's that magic of people with different perspectives, different ideas building into something that is somehow greater than the sum of its individual parts and perspectives.

89
00:06:03,680 --> 00:06:05,280
That's what makes this interesting.

90
00:06:05,280 --> 00:06:07,680
That's what makes music magical.

91
00:06:07,680 --> 00:06:10,560
That's what makes product development interesting.

92
00:06:10,560 --> 00:06:15,840
Especially, you know, in the age of AI when people have the opportunity to, I think,

93
00:06:15,840 --> 00:06:23,440
close themselves off from the messier parts of human interaction, from those moments where you realize that your perspective might be limited,

94
00:06:23,440 --> 00:06:28,479
that somebody else might be able to expose you to something, show you a way of working,

95
00:06:28,479 --> 00:06:31,759
show you a way of seeing that you haven't seen before.

96
00:06:31,759 --> 00:06:40,800
I I think that those interactions, that ability to learn from and build with each other is only going to become more valuable and and more precious,

97
00:06:40,800 --> 00:06:44,800
frankly, as technology continues to do what technology does.

98
00:06:44,800 --> 00:06:46,479
>> Wow, what a beautiful answer.

99
00:06:46,479 --> 00:06:48,319
I love that.

100
00:06:48,319 --> 00:06:50,720
Okay, so let's get to the task at hand.

101
00:06:50,720 --> 00:06:51,039
Yes.

102
00:06:51,039 --> 00:06:58,240
>> So, you're known for writing one of the most popular books in the field of product management called Product Management in Practice.

103
00:06:58,240 --> 00:06:59,680
>> I suppose I am.

104
00:06:59,680 --> 00:07:00,960
>> Yes.

105
00:07:00,960 --> 00:07:07,120
basically describes the job of a product manager, very practically, very specifically,

106
00:07:07,120 --> 00:07:08,880
better than any other book out there.

107
00:07:08,880 --> 00:07:11,680
You have a new book out called impact verse product teams.

108
00:07:11,680 --> 00:07:22,960
I asked you what the goal of this book was and you said the goal was >> what are the steps that individual product teams can take to align their work to business critical outcomes regardless of how their organizations

109
00:07:22,960 --> 00:07:25,120
approach product development.

110
00:07:25,120 --> 00:07:28,560
And I thought this was a really nice way of framing this conversation.

111
00:07:28,560 --> 00:07:32,080
There's two important parts to this sentence that you gave me.

112
00:07:32,080 --> 00:07:40,240
One is aligning your work to business critical outcomes and the other is steps an individual product team can take regardless of how their business functions.

113
00:07:40,240 --> 00:07:41,840
So let me start with this first part.

114
00:07:41,840 --> 00:07:47,039
This is kind of the the you named your book after this concept of impact first.

115
00:07:47,039 --> 00:07:51,440
Why is aligning work to impact and to business critical outcomes so important?

116
00:07:51,440 --> 00:07:59,919
It's important because at the end of the day, it is those business critical outcomes against which you and your team will be evaluated.

117
00:07:59,919 --> 00:08:02,240
That's the reality of working for a business, right?

118
00:08:02,240 --> 00:08:06,720
If you are contributing to the business in a way that the business at large can understand,

119
00:08:06,720 --> 00:08:13,440
that the CEO can understand, that the CFO can understand, if your team is a good investment for the business,

120
00:08:13,440 --> 00:08:16,560
then the business will continue making that investment.

121
00:08:16,560 --> 00:08:22,639
If your team is not a good investment for the business or you don't really know if your team is a good investment for the business,

122
00:08:22,639 --> 00:08:26,319
but you figure you're showing up, so probably it's fine.

123
00:08:26,319 --> 00:08:36,000
You guess, then that puts you in a really tenuous position and a position that I think we've all seen not work out terribly well for everybody in recent history.

124
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:37,760
>> And so what is this a reaction to?

125
00:08:37,760 --> 00:08:42,640
Because I imagine many people hearing this are like, "Of course PMs, product teams, we're driving business impact.

126
00:08:42,640 --> 00:08:43,839
That's why we're here."

127
00:08:43,839 --> 00:08:45,360
That's not actually the case in most cases.

128
00:08:45,360 --> 00:08:47,600
So, first of all, just like >> what is this reaction to?

129
00:08:47,600 --> 00:08:51,200
Is this the reaction to people being like, "Oh, we're just going to build great products.

130
00:08:51,200 --> 00:08:52,959
We're going to listen to customers."

131
00:08:52,959 --> 00:08:54,640
Talk about the the flip side of this.

132
00:08:54,640 --> 00:08:55,839
>> I mean, there's a couple things.

133
00:08:55,839 --> 00:09:01,200
I think the main one is just more product managers and teams are getting laid off.

134
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:05,839
That's a really scary reality right now.

135
00:09:05,839 --> 00:09:11,120
And if you look at the messages that are being conveyed by CEOs when they lay off these teams,

136
00:09:11,120 --> 00:09:13,120
it's, you know, some of them are pretty clear.

137
00:09:13,120 --> 00:09:24,240
The message that Daniel E from Spotify sent out with their layoffs in 2024 said, "We still have too many teams doing work around the work and supporting work rather than focusing on opportunities with real

138
00:09:24,240 --> 00:09:25,360
impact."

139
00:09:25,360 --> 00:09:29,120
And that really struck a nerve because I've been on those supporting teams before.

140
00:09:29,120 --> 00:09:30,880
I've done the work around the work.

141
00:09:30,880 --> 00:09:40,080
And I've assumed that if I was given work around the work to do that surely it must be critical to the business otherwise they wouldn't have hired me to do it.

142
00:09:40,080 --> 00:09:43,040
I I don't think that is a safe assumption to make.

143
00:09:43,040 --> 00:09:54,240
I think especially given that we are no longer in a zero interest rate environment given that hiring and retaining employees ex is you know expensive given

144
00:09:54,240 --> 00:09:57,120
that companies are looking at cost savings.

145
00:09:57,120 --> 00:10:06,720
I think we are in a moment where it is really incumbent upon each product team and each member of each product team to be able to understand,

146
00:10:06,720 --> 00:10:12,399
articulate and work towards the topline business impact of their own work.

147
00:10:12,399 --> 00:10:12,720
>> Awesome.

148
00:10:12,720 --> 00:10:12,959
Okay.

149
00:10:12,959 --> 00:10:20,240
So, where this comes from is one uh if you're not driving something that is directly driving business growth,

150
00:10:20,240 --> 00:10:21,600
you're not as valuable to the company.

151
00:10:21,600 --> 00:10:23,680
You're the kind of person that they'd lay off.

152
00:10:23,680 --> 00:10:25,519
>> There's also a flip side of finding a job.

153
00:10:25,519 --> 00:10:29,839
It feels like if you have shown impact in your resume, here's all the impact I've driven.

154
00:10:29,839 --> 00:10:31,360
This also helps you get hired.

155
00:10:31,360 --> 00:10:31,839
True.

156
00:10:31,839 --> 00:10:32,880
>> Absolutely.

157
00:10:32,880 --> 00:10:33,120
Yeah.

158
00:10:33,120 --> 00:10:37,440
I mean, I I it's the most common resume advice I see, right, is like show the number.

159
00:10:37,440 --> 00:10:38,959
Show the impact.

160
00:10:38,959 --> 00:10:40,079
Say what you did.

161
00:10:40,079 --> 00:10:42,560
I I have a friend who does resume coaching.

162
00:10:42,560 --> 00:10:48,640
And I showed her my resume a couple years ago and she said, "I love your resume except for one thing.

163
00:10:48,640 --> 00:10:50,640
Why do you write like a little girl?

164
00:10:50,640 --> 00:10:51,839
Say what you did.

165
00:10:51,839 --> 00:10:53,600
Say what your contributions were."

166
00:10:53,600 --> 00:10:54,959
Don't say, "I helped.

167
00:10:54,959 --> 00:10:57,360
I may have maybe helped people do this.

168
00:10:57,360 --> 00:10:58,480
Say the impact.

169
00:10:58,480 --> 00:11:00,160
Put the number on it.

170
00:11:00,160 --> 00:11:10,560
And I think I needed to hear that from her because um I think there is a tendency especially for those of us who do really thrive in that collaborative

171
00:11:10,560 --> 00:11:20,959
environment who you know our nature is to not want to take credit for work that could only exist via the contributions of many people with diverse experiences

172
00:11:20,959 --> 00:11:22,160
and perspectives.

173
00:11:22,160 --> 00:11:25,839
It's really hard to say like, well, I did this and I contributed to that.

174
00:11:25,839 --> 00:11:35,120
But that's part of why I wrote this book at the team level because I think for folks like myself who really enjoy and thrive in and enjoy that team environment,

175
00:11:35,120 --> 00:11:40,640
if you can look at the product team as the foundational unit of impact and say we delivered this,

176
00:11:40,640 --> 00:11:48,800
we were able to work together to have this impact for the business, that feels really good and also speaks directly to the work that that team did together.

177
00:11:48,800 --> 00:11:50,079
And >> it's a really interesting insight.

178
00:11:50,079 --> 00:11:58,320
I think a lot of this comes from just PMs naturally are trained to deflect uh credit and to include say we and everything and just this person did that.

179
00:11:58,320 --> 00:12:00,800
So I get where that comes from.

180
00:12:00,800 --> 00:12:10,639
>> Um okay so most listeners will probably still be thinking yes I'm driving impact I'm great well I don't have a problem here I don't need to change need to change anything.

181
00:12:10,639 --> 00:12:13,120
What are some ways to stress test your thinking?

182
00:12:13,120 --> 00:12:17,680
Maybe some questions to ask yourself or maybe your team of just like okay maybe I'm not.

183
00:12:17,680 --> 00:12:26,000
So the first question I ask most of the teams I work with is if you were the CEO of this company,

184
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:29,680
would you fully fund your own team?

185
00:12:29,680 --> 00:12:39,279
And that is a small question that can provoke some big reactions because for me when I was working as a product manager,

186
00:12:39,279 --> 00:12:45,519
I truly believed that my job was to find the next most defensible thing to build.

187
00:12:45,519 --> 00:12:46,320
Build it.

188
00:12:46,320 --> 00:12:53,680
celebrate it, find the next most defensible thing to build, and so on and so forth, rinse and repeat forever and ever.

189
00:12:53,680 --> 00:13:00,240
I kind of assumed that the existence of my team was this righteous fact of the universe,

190
00:13:00,240 --> 00:13:00,480
right?

191
00:13:00,480 --> 00:13:05,279
My team would always be there for all time and it was just a matter of us finding the next thing to work on,

192
00:13:05,279 --> 00:13:13,440
which meant, you know, doing discovery and making concessions to what leadership wanted and doing all that stakeholder management.

193
00:13:13,440 --> 00:13:20,720
But the idea that my team came at a cost to the business that at some point somebody might look at my team on a spreadsheet and say,

194
00:13:20,720 --> 00:13:23,519
"Who are these very expensive people?

195
00:13:23,519 --> 00:13:25,839
Why do we need them?

196
00:13:25,839 --> 00:13:27,920
Do we actually need them?"

197
00:13:27,920 --> 00:13:31,440
It just wasn't something that crossed my mind cuz I wasn't in the room for those conversations.

198
00:13:31,440 --> 00:13:34,560
That wasn't how I was thinking about my team's work.

199
00:13:34,560 --> 00:13:38,240
So, I I like asking this question because it's a perspective shift.

200
00:13:38,240 --> 00:13:47,920
It gets you thinking if you were personally accountable for the existential market level success of this business,

201
00:13:47,920 --> 00:13:52,399
would you invest in your team?

202
00:13:52,399 --> 00:13:57,440
And frankly, most of the people I ask that question to don't know the answer right away.

203
00:13:57,440 --> 00:13:58,560
They're not sure.

204
00:13:58,560 --> 00:14:00,079
They say,"I I think so."

205
00:14:00,079 --> 00:14:01,279
Or, "Yeah, yeah, yeah."

206
00:14:01,279 --> 00:14:05,760
You know, because and and then you can see the gears turning.

207
00:14:05,760 --> 00:14:14,079
And again, to me, that is a risky situation to be in because if you can't answer that question as a member of the team,

208
00:14:14,079 --> 00:14:19,279
nobody else in the organization is going to be as well equipped to answer that question as you are.

209
00:14:19,279 --> 00:14:26,959
So, bringing that question to the team, asking it and answering it proactively and collaboratively and being ready to say,

210
00:14:26,959 --> 00:14:31,279
okay, if we can't answer this confidently, what are the changes we need to make?

211
00:14:31,279 --> 00:14:32,880
Do we need to change our purview?

212
00:14:32,880 --> 00:14:34,959
Do we need to change our goals?

213
00:14:34,959 --> 00:14:36,079
who do we need to talk to?

214
00:14:36,079 --> 00:14:38,639
What do we need to do in order to make this happen?

215
00:14:38,639 --> 00:14:46,959
In order to answer that question confidently, we are much better off having that conversation at the team level and waiting for someone else to

216
00:14:46,959 --> 00:14:50,079
have it for us or at us.

