So, we started having this conversation, you know, what what framework should be used,

625
00:47:05,440 --> 00:47:06,480
how should we do this?

626
00:47:06,480 --> 00:47:09,200
And I I I was not asking very good questions.

627
00:47:09,200 --> 00:47:11,440
I was kind of panicking too to be honest.

628
00:47:11,440 --> 00:47:16,319
And then I asked them, I was like,"Okay, why does this team exist, right?

629
00:47:16,319 --> 00:47:17,920
Why do we why are we doing this at all?

630
00:47:17,920 --> 00:47:21,440
Like why is the business investing in this big team to build all these features?

631
00:47:21,440 --> 00:47:25,839
Why do we care if we're a single product company or a multi-product platform company?"

632
00:47:25,839 --> 00:47:33,440
And one of the team leaders said, "Oh, well actually the customer lifetime value of a multi-product user is much higher than that of a single product user."

633
00:47:33,440 --> 00:47:36,640
And I was like, "Oh, do we know how much higher?"

634
00:47:36,640 --> 00:47:38,480
And they said, "Yeah, we actually have a number on that."

635
00:47:38,480 --> 00:47:47,839
And I was like, "Wow, so like if we had a goal of converting a certain number of single product users to multi-product users,

636
00:47:47,839 --> 00:47:50,319
we know exactly how much revenue is on the lot."

637
00:47:50,319 --> 00:47:52,079
They were like, "Yeah, I guess."

638
00:47:52,079 --> 00:47:57,680
So, so we were able to set a goal and from there we had this conversation about, you know,

639
00:47:57,680 --> 00:48:08,240
what's the number we would need to hit to make this team feel like a good investment and we came to a specific number and that number informed every decision that was made by that team for the rest of the year.

640
00:48:08,240 --> 00:48:18,800
We said by the end of the year we need to convert this many single product users to multi-product users because if we do that there's this much additional revenue which contributes this much to the company's

641
00:48:18,800 --> 00:48:19,920
topline revenue goal.

642
00:48:19,920 --> 00:48:22,319
It's one step away.

643
00:48:22,319 --> 00:48:27,839
And when they went and shared that goal with company leadership, they got it right away.

644
00:48:27,839 --> 00:48:29,680
They didn't have to say,"Well, why is this valuable?"

645
00:48:29,680 --> 00:48:32,000
They didn't have to say, "What are your other OKRs?

646
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:33,119
Show us the deck."

647
00:48:33,119 --> 00:48:34,400
They got it.

648
00:48:34,400 --> 00:48:41,520
And that gave them so much leeway to make bolder decisions, to work more closely with other teams,

649
00:48:41,520 --> 00:48:44,240
to ask for the resources they needed.

650
00:48:44,240 --> 00:48:54,960
And that process of of arriving at that goal, that goal that is impactful and specific and one step away from what the company cares about the most is probably the the most

651
00:48:54,960 --> 00:49:01,680
valuable way I have spent my time with teams of late because once you get to that, you see how everything else flows from there.

652
00:49:01,680 --> 00:49:08,559
>> And the implication here is that if it's too far away from helping from people understanding what the hell are you guys even doing to help the business,

653
00:49:08,559 --> 00:49:10,240
that's the problem you want to avoid.

654
00:49:10,240 --> 00:49:18,000
So exactly like so one extreme is uh I don't know like it probably doesn't make sense for your team to have exactly the same goal as the company.

655
00:49:18,000 --> 00:49:21,040
Say your company's trying to grow 100 million revenue, right?

656
00:49:21,040 --> 00:49:23,200
Like that's not going to be your team's goal.

657
00:49:23,200 --> 00:49:26,800
>> So it's almost like at that extreme is what's one step away from that?

658
00:49:26,800 --> 00:49:29,040
What's your contribution to that company goal?

659
00:49:29,040 --> 00:49:31,599
The other end is just like some 10 level deep.

660
00:49:31,599 --> 00:49:37,040
We're going to improve conversion of this random step which is going to grow this thing which grows that and then that grows revenue.

661
00:49:37,040 --> 00:49:38,160
Exactly.

662
00:49:38,160 --> 00:49:43,040
What is your guidance on revenue-based goals as goals for teams?

663
00:49:43,040 --> 00:49:45,040
>> You know, I think again it depends.

664
00:49:45,040 --> 00:49:50,800
I I know people have very strong opinions about teams should always or should never have revenue- based goals.

665
00:49:50,800 --> 00:49:52,240
I don't think it's that simple.

666
00:49:52,240 --> 00:50:03,359
I think sometimes yes, if your company is working towards revenue, having a revenue-based goal makes sense or at least being able to put some value in terms of revenue on the work that your

667
00:50:03,359 --> 00:50:04,400
team is doing.

668
00:50:04,400 --> 00:50:11,040
I've worked with some startups where they actively are not going after revenue because right now the name of the game is growth,

669
00:50:11,040 --> 00:50:11,280
right?

670
00:50:11,280 --> 00:50:16,800
They want to show that they have enough users to raise that next round of investment.

671
00:50:16,800 --> 00:50:27,520
I actually worked with one startup where their revenue was going up and their number of users was going up and we had to have a really interesting conversation around which one actually matters to our investors.

672
00:50:27,520 --> 00:50:33,680
And we kind of wound up developing these two scenarios, the high growth scenario and the low growth scenario.

673
00:50:33,680 --> 00:50:38,160
And talking to the product team, it was really clear that there was like no way they were going to hit the high growth scenario.

674
00:50:38,160 --> 00:50:46,319
So they pivoted to focus on profitability so they could build more runway and raise that next round as a smaller business with a sustainable revenue base.

675
00:50:46,319 --> 00:50:51,440
So I get why people are hesitant to commit to revenue goals.

676
00:50:51,440 --> 00:50:59,920
I think that there are certainly situations where revenue goals would be too broad or not exactly what the business needs.

677
00:50:59,920 --> 00:51:08,240
But at the end of the day, money is how the impact of most teams is going to be measured.

678
00:51:08,240 --> 00:51:17,440
And if you don't have a point of view on why your team is a good investment, either in the money return it brings or in another return

679
00:51:17,440 --> 00:51:25,520
that is equally or more important to the business, then again, that feels like a tenuous and risky position to be in.

680
00:51:25,520 --> 00:51:28,640
to kind of get people's brains noodling in the right direction.

681
00:51:28,640 --> 00:51:35,839
What are some examples of good goals like specific goals that your teams have set that are one step away from a company goal?

682
00:51:35,839 --> 00:51:38,640
What are just some examples without naming companies?

683
00:51:38,640 --> 00:51:47,440
>> I have a a story to tell to that effect which also sets up the second step here which is to keep impact first at every step.

684
00:51:47,440 --> 00:51:56,559
So I worked with a growth team at a a a tech company that that is beloved by many people and I was brought on to help them set OKRs,

685
00:51:56,559 --> 00:51:56,960
right?

686
00:51:56,960 --> 00:52:03,200
The company was doing OKRs across the board and this team was going to set its growth OKRs.

687
00:52:03,200 --> 00:52:09,359
So they had done a lot of reading, a lot of research into how to do OKRs the right way.

688
00:52:09,359 --> 00:52:15,680
They had read unfortunately they had not read Radical Focus um or they hopefully would have done things differently.

689
00:52:15,680 --> 00:52:16,880
They had read a lot of other books.

690
00:52:16,880 --> 00:52:21,040
They had printed out a lot of articles and they said, you know, we're going to make sure we get this right.

691
00:52:21,040 --> 00:52:31,760
We're going to put together a slide deck that has five to seven objectives with five to seven key results each and each key result is going to have an owner and we're going to make sure that people are accountable

692
00:52:31,760 --> 00:52:35,920
for it and we're going to really really do this the right way.

693
00:52:35,920 --> 00:52:39,440
We're going to get that middle piece perfect.

694
00:52:39,440 --> 00:52:44,960
So, they spent a long time working on these OKRs.

695
00:52:44,960 --> 00:52:46,400
OKR season ends.

696
00:52:46,400 --> 00:52:51,440
They file away the OKR deck, not to be seen until the next OKR season.

697
00:52:51,440 --> 00:52:56,000
We reconvene and spend a whole day scoring all of the OKRs, right?

698
00:52:56,000 --> 00:53:02,480
And there are heated conversations about what's a 6 versus a 7, is this a 0.9?

699
00:53:02,480 --> 00:53:05,200
Who really should be the owner of this key result?

700
00:53:05,200 --> 00:53:07,040
Who contributed the most to it?

701
00:53:07,040 --> 00:53:10,720
And um you know, we we get through this whole conversation.

702
00:53:10,720 --> 00:53:16,319
Everyone's tired and and I'm like, I there's just one question I need to ask.

703
00:53:16,319 --> 00:53:23,599
I'm so sorry to do this to y'all, but how does this all add up to the company level growth goals?

704
00:53:23,599 --> 00:53:24,800
People kind of look around.

705
00:53:24,800 --> 00:53:28,240
They're like, "Well, that that wasn't what we did."

706
00:53:28,240 --> 00:53:35,359
Like, we set our team level OKRs and we went through the process and we made sure and and we we followed the OKRs.

707
00:53:35,359 --> 00:53:45,119
thought about the OKRs and I said, "Yeah, but the the company has a a goal of let's call it bringing on a million new users in this year.

708
00:53:45,119 --> 00:53:47,040
We're a growth team.

709
00:53:47,040 --> 00:53:49,920
How many users did we bring on?"

710
00:53:49,920 --> 00:53:56,400
And there's a moment of silence and the leader of this team is really really good leader.

711
00:53:56,400 --> 00:54:00,000
She stands up and she's like, "Okay, we're going to do things differently."

712
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:06,319
She steps up to the whiteboard, puts 1 million on the right end of the whiteboard, draws a line.

713
00:54:06,319 --> 00:54:07,440
This is the year.

714
00:54:07,440 --> 00:54:08,960
Draws a little tick on the line.

715
00:54:08,960 --> 00:54:09,920
This is where we are now.

716
00:54:09,920 --> 00:54:12,079
It's a smaller number than a million.

717
00:54:12,079 --> 00:54:15,200
This is where we need to get to.

718
00:54:15,200 --> 00:54:19,839
If our conversation doesn't start with this, I don't want to have the conversation.

719
00:54:19,839 --> 00:54:28,559
And if you are 51% sure that a different approach is going to get us 1% closer, I expect you to advocate for that approach.

720
00:54:28,559 --> 00:54:34,480
And this is now how we are going to do everything.

721
00:54:34,480 --> 00:54:42,000
And I think about that all the time because it's subtracting steps, right?

722
00:54:42,000 --> 00:54:44,319
It's making things less complicated.

723
00:54:44,319 --> 00:54:46,640
It actually is doing exactly what you described.

724
00:54:46,640 --> 00:54:48,800
It's saying like this is what the company cares about.

725
00:54:48,800 --> 00:54:50,160
We're the growth team.

726
00:54:50,160 --> 00:54:54,640
We need to figure out how everything we're doing contributes to this.

727
00:54:54,640 --> 00:54:58,319
And that story really stuck with me.

728
00:54:58,319 --> 00:55:00,720
because it seems like it should be obvious, right?

729
00:55:00,720 --> 00:55:06,000
If you're the growth team at a company with a growth goal, obviously that's going to be something you care about.

730
00:55:06,000 --> 00:55:12,079
But it's so easy in the day-to-day work of setting these intermediate goals, of doing strategy,

731
00:55:12,079 --> 00:55:18,559
of doing the things we do to make things just a little bit more complicated that they need to be.

732
00:55:18,559 --> 00:55:29,760
So for this particular team and this particular moment, a good goal was looking at the company level goal and saying if we're the team that's driving growth,

733
00:55:29,760 --> 00:55:31,040
we're accountable for this.

734
00:55:31,040 --> 00:55:37,839
We're going to step up and we're going to do everything we can to make sure the company meets its ambition.

735
00:55:37,839 --> 00:55:42,079
And it's so obvious, you know, if you're if you come at it from the perspective you shared earlier,

736
00:55:42,079 --> 00:55:45,599
if you're the CEO, well, would you fund this team?

737
00:55:45,599 --> 00:55:48,319
Like if you see our goal is a million users.

738
00:55:48,319 --> 00:55:53,040
This team will drive us 100,000 users assuming that's a lot for you.

739
00:55:53,040 --> 00:55:59,599
Like obviously we want that team to do great and we're going to give them the resources to do that because we they're going to contribute meaningfully to the goal.

740
00:55:59,599 --> 00:56:01,920
Like it's very obvious as you see it.

741
00:56:01,920 --> 00:56:05,920
Uh the trick is a lot of people think they are doing that and they're not.

742
00:56:05,920 --> 00:56:15,680
One maybe one heristic I think about as you're talking is just like how do you know if you're doing this is there should be a very simple spreadsheet formula of just here's the company goal here is your goal there

743
00:56:15,680 --> 00:56:25,760
should be like one simple formula that translates up that adds to it >> one why statement and or one mathematical operator is usually the way I think about it >> there we go

744
00:56:25,760 --> 00:56:36,240
>> um in some cases like the story I told about that fintech company it's something like upgraded users that's one step right you multiply that by the

745
00:56:36,240 --> 00:56:38,880
increased customer lifetime value.

746
00:56:38,880 --> 00:56:42,319
In some cases, it's a smaller unit of the same thing.

747
00:56:42,319 --> 00:56:46,880
So, it's a subset of the revenue or growth that the company's trying to deliver.

748
00:56:46,880 --> 00:56:51,440
I worked with a company recently that had a team rebuilding their ad tech platform.

749
00:56:51,440 --> 00:56:53,520
This is a big company that does a lot of different things.

750
00:56:53,520 --> 00:56:57,920
And at the heart of all of their different offerings is this ad tech platform.

751
00:56:57,920 --> 00:57:06,559
And I was brought on to do a dayong workshop with this company because this was a really important team and they were struggling to figure out what success looked like.

752
00:57:06,559 --> 00:57:09,040
So I said, "Okay, what are your goals?"

753
00:57:09,040 --> 00:57:12,319
And they said, "Here's the deck with our goals."

754
00:57:12,319 --> 00:57:14,319
And I said, "That's a lot of goals.

755
00:57:14,319 --> 00:57:17,599
I I wouldn't be able to make decisions with those goals."

756
00:57:17,599 --> 00:57:18,559
They said,"Oh, wait, wait, wait.

757
00:57:18,559 --> 00:57:20,000
No, we also have a Murro board."

758
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:23,520
Cuz we went through this and we decided the deck was too much, so we also have a Miro board.

759
00:57:23,520 --> 00:57:27,839
But as neuro boards tend to do, it kind of grew and grew and grew in all directions.

760
00:57:27,839 --> 00:57:30,720
So now it's a big neurobo.

761
00:57:30,720 --> 00:57:33,599
Turned out they had two muro boards because they had tried to do this twice.

762
00:57:33,599 --> 00:57:44,240
So we sat down and we did this really interesting kind of subtractive exercise where everybody got a post-it note to write down what they think the most important goal of the

763
00:57:44,240 --> 00:57:44,799
team is.

764
00:57:44,799 --> 00:57:48,079
And then they would pair up and they would have to make it smaller each time.

765
00:57:48,079 --> 00:57:49,040
Make it more concise.

766
00:57:49,040 --> 00:57:51,040
If there were two things, get it down to one thing.

767
00:57:51,040 --> 00:57:53,280
If there were 10 words, bring it down to eight words.

768
00:57:53,280 --> 00:57:56,559
Make it smaller and more concise each time.

769
00:57:56,559 --> 00:57:58,559
And we came up with two options.

770
00:57:58,559 --> 00:58:07,520
One was, you know, build a fantastic, wonderful, magical, beautiful platform to increase our team's profits by 20%.

771
00:58:07,520 --> 00:58:08,319
Fair enough.

772
00:58:08,319 --> 00:58:18,319
The other one was build a stupendous, wonderful, fantastic platform to increase our team's profits in the next financial year from 20 million to 100 million pounds.

773
00:58:18,319 --> 00:58:23,920
And I'm looking at these and I'm like, okay, so we we know that there is an expectation of revenue here,

774
00:58:23,920 --> 00:58:24,319
right?

775
00:58:24,319 --> 00:58:32,720
There's an expectation that we will drive profitability, but one of these is 20% and the other is 500%.

776
00:58:32,720 --> 00:58:35,760
Where do these numbers come from?

777
00:58:35,760 --> 00:58:40,640
And you know the the folks who had said 20%, they were like that that feels like a good return,

778
00:58:40,640 --> 00:58:42,079
right?

779
00:58:42,079 --> 00:58:48,480
And what's interesting was, you know, when I was telling the story when I was giving some talks recently and people would kind of laugh like,

780
00:58:48,480 --> 00:58:59,760
oh, they named the wrong number, but like they were so brave to do that and them saying 20% is what actually unlocked the conversation at the team level because somebody else

781
00:58:59,760 --> 00:59:03,440
in the room heard that and said, "Wait, I do remember something about profits.

782
00:59:03,440 --> 00:59:08,000
There was some target we were supposed to hit, but I think I remember it being a lot bigger than that."

783
00:59:08,000 --> 00:59:19,440
They actually went back and found a town hall that their VP had given and buried in a slide in that town hall was this 100 million pound profit target by the end of the

784
00:59:19,440 --> 00:59:22,319
next financial year.

785
00:59:22,319 --> 00:59:26,400
So they have this number and they start to go like, "Oh gosh, that's a lot."

786
00:59:26,400 --> 00:59:28,880
Like, but you know, it's a whole financial year.

787
00:59:28,880 --> 00:59:30,079
It'll be fine.

788
00:59:30,079 --> 00:59:34,319
And we do, again, inspired by that leader I work with, I just put this out on a whiteboard.

789
00:59:34,319 --> 00:59:37,920
I'm like, "All right, 100 million in profits by the end of the next financial year."

790
00:59:37,920 --> 00:59:38,960
Right now, we're here.

791
00:59:38,960 --> 00:59:40,640
What else should be on this timeline?

792
00:59:40,640 --> 00:59:43,520
Somebody said, "Well, we're launching this in October."

793
00:59:43,520 --> 00:59:44,960
So, I put October up there.

794
00:59:44,960 --> 00:59:53,520
I go, "Okay, so if we don't ship anything until October, and right now it's March, how much profit do we make until that?"

795
00:59:53,520 --> 00:59:55,760
I said, "About 10 million."

796
00:59:55,760 --> 00:59:56,000
Okay.

797
00:59:56,000 --> 01:00:05,240
So, so that means that between October and March, we need to generate 90 million pounds of profits.

798
01:00:06,000 --> 01:00:12,160
And this team, I was worried that they were going to freak out or they were going to be like,

799
01:00:12,160 --> 01:00:12,960
"Oh, we can't do this.

800
01:00:12,960 --> 01:00:13,680
It's impossible."

801
01:00:13,680 --> 01:00:18,319
But they they were like, "Okay, it's time to step up.

802
01:00:18,319 --> 01:00:20,319
It's time to do all these things that we need to do.

803
01:00:20,319 --> 01:00:21,359
We need to ship sooner.

804
01:00:21,359 --> 01:00:22,640
We need to do more validation.

805
01:00:22,640 --> 01:00:24,000
We need to do more testing.

806
01:00:24,000 --> 01:00:25,520
Can we commercialize things sooner?

807
01:00:25,520 --> 01:00:29,200
Can we do more discovery to make sure that this is really going to have the impact we need to have?

808
01:00:29,200 --> 01:00:30,720
Why are we doing this whole big relaunch?

809
01:00:30,720 --> 01:00:32,880
Why don't we rebuild individual things?

810
01:00:32,880 --> 01:00:36,160
What impact would we have if we brought more people in top of funnel now?

811
01:00:36,160 --> 01:00:38,799
Can we begin building our user base and then upgrade that user base?

812
01:00:38,799 --> 01:00:41,280
What are the trade-offs if we do that versus if we bring people?

813
01:00:41,280 --> 01:00:47,839
All those things that that I think is is really the the heart and the intent of these best practices.

814
01:00:47,839 --> 01:00:52,000
They came to life because this team had clarity.

815
01:00:52,000 --> 01:01:03,680
they understood like okay we are accountable for something which is specific enough to drive some real urgency and which is impactful enough that we have to get out there and do all these things that we're

816
01:01:03,680 --> 01:01:05,440
supposed to do.

817
01:01:05,440 --> 01:01:14,160
So you know that to me is a really good example of how if you start with this question of like what is what is expected of this team?

818
01:01:14,160 --> 01:01:16,160
What does success look like for us?

819
01:01:16,160 --> 01:01:24,559
It'll often lead you to kind of the right kind of neighborhood of what kind of unit of measure you want to look for,

820
01:01:24,559 --> 01:01:27,520
how the business is going to look to you, whether they're looking directly at revenue,

821
01:01:27,520 --> 01:01:29,440
whether they're looking at something else.

822
01:01:29,440 --> 01:01:30,880
Okay, these stories are awesome.

823
01:01:30,880 --> 01:01:36,640
So, basically, so far the two steps uh that you've illustrated here of doing this correctly,

824
01:01:36,640 --> 01:01:38,160
step one is set teams goal.

825
01:01:38,160 --> 01:01:40,880
Set team goals that are close to company goals.

826
01:01:40,880 --> 01:01:44,799
And then step two is do this at every step of the product building process.

827
01:01:44,799 --> 01:01:46,880
It's not just a onetime thing at the beginning, >> right?

828
01:01:46,880 --> 01:01:51,680
As you're doing OKRs, like that team I talked about, you know, when you're thinking about your company strategy,

829
01:01:51,680 --> 01:01:58,640
when you're writing epics, whatever it is, keep that impactful goal top of mind.

830
01:01:58,640 --> 01:01:59,760
Don't let it slip away.

831
01:01:59,760 --> 01:02:02,400
Don't let it get cascaded into oblivion.

832
01:02:02,400 --> 01:02:05,760
>> Because to your point, the examples you shared where you think you're like you're just like,

833
01:02:05,760 --> 01:02:06,640
"Cool, we have our goal.

834
01:02:06,640 --> 01:02:15,280
Let's And then you spend months doing this thing and then you forget, okay, this actually got disconnected from the company goal and everything you've worked hard to do is just no one cares.

835
01:02:15,280 --> 01:02:16,400
>> Yeah.

836
01:02:16,400 --> 01:02:16,960
Okay.

837
01:02:16,960 --> 01:02:18,720
Uh what is step three?

838
01:02:18,720 --> 01:02:23,760
>> Step three is to connect every bit of work back to impact.

839
01:02:23,760 --> 01:02:26,880
So this is when we get to the prioritization piece, right?

840
01:02:26,880 --> 01:02:38,640
So impact estimation is something that is written about quite well quite extensively in product management stuff but it's something that it's easy to not

841
01:02:38,640 --> 01:02:40,079
do.

842
01:02:40,079 --> 01:02:47,440
Um, you know, I work with a lot of teams that want to know again the right best practice for doing prioritization,

843
01:02:47,440 --> 01:02:55,040
whether that's, you know, should we use ice or rice or Moscow or whatever it is, what's the right way to do prioritization?

844
01:02:55,040 --> 01:03:06,079
And, you know, again, like it depends, but if you don't have a clear and specific sense of what impact means,

845
01:03:06,079 --> 01:03:08,079
you can't really prioritize effectively.

846
01:03:08,079 --> 01:03:13,280
So this is where again everything comes back to that first step of the way you set goals.

847
01:03:13,280 --> 01:03:19,200
So that team I told you about that had the goal of converting single product users to multi-product users.

848
01:03:19,200 --> 01:03:22,960
One of the product managers on that team came back to me a few months later and said,

849
01:03:22,960 --> 01:03:26,240
"Hey Matt, I could really use your help figuring out how to do prioritization.

850
01:03:26,240 --> 01:03:26,880
Should we do ICE?

851
01:03:26,880 --> 01:03:27,920
Should we do Rice?

852
01:03:27,920 --> 01:03:28,799
Should we do Moscow?"

853
01:03:28,799 --> 01:03:39,119
I I put together an ICE matrix where I scored impact and I scored certainty and I scored effort and I multiplied each one by each one and I have a list of the things we should do and I said that's

854
01:03:39,119 --> 01:03:46,960
awesome and and I do really think it's awesome when people take the initiative to do the thing to say like I put this together let's walk through it.

855
01:03:46,960 --> 01:03:50,400
So when they showed me this you know I said let's start with impact.

856
01:03:50,400 --> 01:03:52,720
They're like okay well here's the score for each one.

857
01:03:52,720 --> 01:03:56,160
I was like how do you what's the score?

858
01:03:56,160 --> 01:03:57,920
They're like oh you know it's a lot of different things.

859
01:03:57,920 --> 01:04:05,119
And I said, okay, well, we have a team goal of a certain specific number of users we need to convert by the end of the year.

860
01:04:05,119 --> 01:04:08,480
So, let's try to express impact as a function of that goal.

861
01:04:08,480 --> 01:04:18,160
So, rather than an abstract score, what is the most number of users we could convert in each of these different scenarios?

862
01:04:18,160 --> 01:04:22,880
And understandably, they were kind of like, well, you know, I don't know exactly like it might like,

863
01:04:22,880 --> 01:04:24,160
let's just let's just work through it.

864
01:04:24,160 --> 01:04:25,280
We don't have to be precise, right?

865
01:04:25,280 --> 01:04:30,240
It's called impact estimation, not impact getting perfect number.

866
01:04:30,240 --> 01:04:34,240
So, you know, for one of them, they were like, "Well, we can do this landing page."

867
01:04:34,240 --> 01:04:36,559
I'm like, "Okay, well, how many people hit the landing page?"

868
01:04:36,559 --> 01:04:38,400
And they were like, "Not that many.

869
01:04:38,400 --> 01:04:39,920
Like, maybe a few hundred."

870
01:04:39,920 --> 01:04:40,880
I'm like, "Okay, cool.

871
01:04:40,880 --> 01:04:43,680
So, that's maybe a few hundred."

872
01:04:43,680 --> 01:04:45,839
And and there was one thing which they were really reluctant.

873
01:04:45,839 --> 01:04:51,359
It had a a high effort score and a medium certainty score.

874
01:04:51,359 --> 01:04:56,720
And what they basically said was like, look, if we really wanted to do this, we could redesign the entire onboarding experience,

875
01:04:56,720 --> 01:04:57,119
right?

876
01:04:57,119 --> 01:05:03,039
We could make it so that rather than us trying to like retroactively shuttle people into multi-product usage,

877
01:05:03,039 --> 01:05:08,240
we can understand them right when they join and get them into the right category of user right away.

878
01:05:08,240 --> 01:05:10,799
I'm like, that sounds amazing.

879
01:05:10,799 --> 01:05:12,640
What's the most impact that could have?

880
01:05:12,640 --> 01:05:24,559
And they were like, it would get us all the way there if we did it right, but we'd have to work with these other teams and we'd have to work with marketing and there are so many dependencies and so many things outside of our control that we don't know if we

881
01:05:24,559 --> 01:05:25,359
could do it.

882
01:05:25,359 --> 01:05:26,799
And I said, that's okay.

883
01:05:26,799 --> 01:05:30,160
Like these are the trade-offs we make as product managers.

884
01:05:30,160 --> 01:05:36,319
You will have some things to work on that are going to have less impact but might be easier and more certain to deliver.

885
01:05:36,319 --> 01:05:41,920
But if this thing could get us all the way there, if it's really the only thing we're looking at,

886
01:05:41,920 --> 01:05:48,799
which has really any chance of getting us to our goal, which remember we came up with to answer the question,

887
01:05:48,799 --> 01:05:56,079
what does this team need to deliver to be a good investment for the business, then I I think it's it's worth going for it.

888
01:05:56,079 --> 01:05:58,799
It's worth having those conversations with other product teams.

889
01:05:58,799 --> 01:06:00,880
It's worth talking to folks in marketing.

890
01:06:00,880 --> 01:06:05,920
it's worth, you know, stretching ourselves a little bit and saying this is going to be challenging to do,

891
01:06:05,920 --> 01:06:11,760
but if we can do it, we can really deliver on something which we're going to feel great about.

892
01:06:11,760 --> 01:06:22,079
So, you know, the the way that that third step manifests itself the most frequently tactically is are we estimating and measuring impact in the

893
01:06:22,079 --> 01:06:25,440
same unit of measure as our goals?

894
01:06:25,440 --> 01:06:30,559
Because if we're doing that, then we're keeping ourselves honest and we're saying, "Does this actually have a chance of contributing?"

895
01:06:30,559 --> 01:06:37,440
Whereas, again, if we get really clever and we come up with a proprietary scoring system and all these little intermediate steps,

896
01:06:37,440 --> 01:06:41,760
we can feel like we're doing really awesome work and being very, very terribly smart,

897
01:06:41,760 --> 01:06:51,520
but we again run the risk that we are going to lose our connection with why we're setting about to do this work in the first place.

898
01:06:51,520 --> 01:06:55,359
>> Such an important and often easily overlooked point.

899
01:06:55,359 --> 01:07:05,599
idea that when you're doing rice or whatever version of ice that you do that impact should be based on impact to your goal which is one level removed from the

900
01:07:05,599 --> 01:07:15,680
company goal such like it feels so obvious as you talk about it and I hope most people know this but I feel like that's something people forget just like what is impact oh yeah customers will be

901
01:07:15,680 --> 01:07:25,280
happier again this is not easy work right working in Prada means that we have so many different perspectives so many different folks who have so different priorities.

902
01:07:25,280 --> 01:07:33,920
You know, the stakeholder management piece of this is relentless and exhausting and it's really really easy to lose sight of this

903
01:07:33,920 --> 01:07:41,119
stuff and it takes work and discipline and and as you said bravery to keep bringing it back.

904
01:07:41,119 --> 01:07:52,079
But I think again it is not only the right thing to do, but it it helps you at the end of the day have a little bit more of a a boundary

905
01:07:52,079 --> 01:07:58,640
between the work you're doing at your job and the stuff you're good at in your life.

906
01:07:58,640 --> 01:08:08,160
>> Speaking of boundaries, a lot of the advice you share will involve people saying no and pushing back and convincing people they're wrong,

907
01:08:08,160 --> 01:08:09,280
which is very hard.

908
01:08:09,280 --> 01:08:12,000
That's not a natural happy place for most people.

909
01:08:12,000 --> 01:08:15,000
>> Nope.

910
01:08:15,440 --> 01:08:16,640
>> What advice do you have?

911
01:08:16,640 --> 01:08:24,239
What have you learned works well for pushing back, helping people see how they're not uh what they want you to build is wrong?

912
01:08:24,239 --> 01:08:24,480
>> Yeah.

913
01:08:24,480 --> 01:08:30,799
So, this is where I have the uh the benefit, I suppose, of being a conflict averse people pleaser.

914
01:08:30,799 --> 01:08:42,480
So, I've been uh I've been through this and I think the thing I am proudest of saying in product management practice is

915
01:08:42,480 --> 01:08:48,480
that if you're doing product management really well, you never have to say yes and you never have to say no.

916
01:08:48,480 --> 01:08:52,560
You're giving people options and you're helping them understand the trade-offs.

917
01:08:52,560 --> 01:08:56,640
So, in keeping with this idea that there are things outside of your control, you know,

918
01:08:56,640 --> 01:09:00,159
as a product manager, you're not always going to be the one who makes the decision.

919
01:09:00,159 --> 01:09:11,759
There are going to be other people who come to you and say build this or who say I don't see the value in that do this do that I want this I want that you know if those people are in a position of formal authority in the

920
01:09:11,759 --> 01:09:23,199
organization I've certainly never had luck telling them no furthermore I've found myself in situations where they just know things that I don't know where they're pursuing

921
01:09:23,199 --> 01:09:33,359
an acquisition so there are certain things that we have to do or can't do where you know there's some serious ious financial challenge that they're working their way through right now which is

922
01:09:33,359 --> 01:09:38,880
shifting around priorities but they are not at liberty to discuss that with the broader organization.

923
01:09:38,880 --> 01:09:48,560
It is quite possible that the folks who are asking you to do things that don't make sense have access to information that you don't.

924
01:09:48,560 --> 01:10:01,440
And that in trying to convince them otherwise, you are not only going to fail, but you are going to lose some of that trust

925
01:10:01,440 --> 01:10:08,080
and degrade that relationship that could in time be really important for you.

926
01:10:08,080 --> 01:10:18,080
So I think the challenge is to say like all right you want me to build this thing maybe let's look at the different things if you're going through these steps if you say like you know I understand

927
01:10:18,080 --> 01:10:29,760
here's what our team's goals are here's the stuff we're prioritizing here's the impact we think it could have if you're coming to me with something which is going to have more impact heck yeah I would love to build that sounds amazing

928
01:10:29,760 --> 01:10:40,320
but if it has an unclear impact or if it doesn't tie into this then we might need to adjust the impact we're seeking to have right if this is suddenly really important as with that story that was

929
01:10:40,320 --> 01:10:41,520
told in the book, right?

930
01:10:41,520 --> 01:10:43,760
Sometimes it's like, "All right, we got to do this.

931
01:10:43,760 --> 01:10:48,560
Sure, that means that our impact projection is going to have to be adjusted this much."

932
01:10:48,560 --> 01:10:50,239
You're not saying no, you're not saying yes.

933
01:10:50,239 --> 01:10:55,760
You're helping someone who is in a position to make a decision understand the trade-offs that go into that decision.

934
01:10:55,760 --> 01:11:00,239
And again, if you can do that, you're going to go home at the end of the day feeling better.

935
01:11:00,239 --> 01:11:08,880
you're going to feel less like you lost a battle or that you were, you know, overridden by an unjust tyrant and it's going to be more like,

936
01:11:08,880 --> 01:11:14,239
okay, I made sure they had all the information I would want to have if I were making that decision.

937
01:11:14,239 --> 01:11:19,120
That decision is ultimately theirs to make and I'm going to do the best I can.

938
01:11:19,120 --> 01:11:20,239
Tell me if you disagree.

939
01:11:20,239 --> 01:11:27,520
In my experience, you also want to recommend a path because a lot of people don't want PMs just here's all the options.

940
01:11:27,520 --> 01:11:29,360
I have no opinion, no bias of any kind.

941
01:11:29,360 --> 01:11:30,239
you decide.

942
01:11:30,239 --> 01:11:33,280
Um, I find it people want you to have a perspective.

943
01:11:33,280 --> 01:11:33,760
>> Absolutely.

944
01:11:33,760 --> 01:11:37,280
Options on a recommendation is kind of the magic the magic formula.

945
01:11:37,280 --> 01:11:48,080
I did when I was working with Mailchimp, we actually did a workshop with with all the product managers at the company where we had people like roleplay trying to sell in a single option versus

946
01:11:48,080 --> 01:11:51,840
multiple options with a recommendation.

947
01:11:51,840 --> 01:11:58,719
And it was amazing how when you present a single option, people's instinct is just to like,

948
01:11:58,719 --> 01:12:06,239
well, I don't know, like you start poking holes in it, not because you're a jerk, but because you're looking at one thing and you're like,

949
01:12:06,239 --> 01:12:06,960
oh, what about this?

950
01:12:06,960 --> 01:12:07,440
What about that?

951
01:12:07,440 --> 01:12:12,560
Again, all of your own anxieties and and fears and the things that you don't feel represented in there and where where you're worried,

952
01:12:12,560 --> 01:12:17,679
what if this happens, what if that happens, all of that kind of detracts from the momentum.

953
01:12:17,679 --> 01:12:19,600
Whereas, if you come in and say, "Here are three options.

954
01:12:19,600 --> 01:12:20,320
Here are the trade-offs.

955
01:12:20,320 --> 01:12:22,000
here's the one we recommend.

956
01:12:22,000 --> 01:12:29,360
Then every little bit of back and forth makes those options clearer and stronger.

957
01:12:29,360 --> 01:12:32,640
Uh I feel like people might miss that nuance in the way we talked about it.

958
01:12:32,640 --> 01:12:35,520
So I think that's a really important point to make there.

959
01:12:35,520 --> 01:12:39,520
Let me come back to the three steps just for folks that are just like, "Oh, I'm excited.

960
01:12:39,520 --> 01:12:40,239
I'm motivated.

961
01:12:40,239 --> 01:12:42,640
I'm going to change the way we operate."

962
01:12:42,640 --> 01:12:44,159
Uh I'll summarize real quick.

963
01:12:44,159 --> 01:12:47,440
So step one is set team goals close to company goals.

964
01:12:47,440 --> 01:12:50,320
Step two is keep impact first at every step.

965
01:12:50,320 --> 01:12:53,600
Don't forget as you're building throughout the year.

966
01:12:53,600 --> 01:12:57,920
And then step three is connect every bit of work back to impact.

967
01:12:57,920 --> 01:12:59,600
>> Yeah.

968
01:12:59,600 --> 01:13:06,320
>> I think again it's important to remind people this may be hard and annoying and maybe things are going fine.

969
01:13:06,320 --> 01:13:10,960
Everyone's telling you what to build, you're building it, shipping it, things are it seems to be going all right.

970
01:13:10,960 --> 01:13:19,600
I think an important part of this is just like uh if you believe what you're building is not helping the business grow and succeed,

971
01:13:19,600 --> 01:13:27,600
either they'll let you go someday because you're not doing something that matters or the business will not work out and you'll be in trouble.

972
01:13:27,600 --> 01:13:36,480
So it's like even if you don't want to do this something like there's you need to really seriously think about this even though it's really hard.

973
01:13:36,480 --> 01:13:37,360
>> Yeah.

974
01:13:37,360 --> 01:13:39,199
>> But maybe let me just think of that a little bit.

975
01:13:39,199 --> 01:13:40,480
Say the business is doing great.

976
01:13:40,480 --> 01:13:41,199
everything's great.

977
01:13:41,199 --> 01:13:46,000
CEO is telling you all the things to build, the sales guys and girls are just like here ship these features,

978
01:13:46,000 --> 01:13:48,560
everything's great and everything's working, business is growing.

979
01:13:48,560 --> 01:13:51,280
What thoughts there just like is it just nah, leave it alone.

980
01:13:51,280 --> 01:13:55,920
Or is your sense, okay, most often this will not last and you should really start to work on these skills.

981
01:13:55,920 --> 01:13:56,719
>> You know, it's funny.

982
01:13:56,719 --> 01:14:08,000
The teams I've worked with when things are going well are sometimes just as anxious as the teams I've worked with when things are going poorly because they have a hard time attributing success to what they're

983
01:14:08,000 --> 01:14:08,480
doing, right?

984
01:14:08,480 --> 01:14:14,320
They'll look at it and they'll say, "Yeah, we're doing great, but I think that honestly has more to do with marketing than it does with us."

985
01:14:14,320 --> 01:14:17,920
Or, "Yeah, we're doing great, but we're just in the right place at the right time.

986
01:14:17,920 --> 01:14:20,080
Our our business is doing really well.

987
01:14:20,080 --> 01:14:21,440
Our sector is doing really well.

988
01:14:21,440 --> 01:14:24,640
We're just growing along with everyone else who's growing."

989
01:14:24,640 --> 01:14:32,800
And I I think as with most things, if you approach it with curiosity, there's a lot to learn from it.

990
01:14:32,800 --> 01:14:37,600
So if you look at it and you say, "Yeah, we can't necessarily take sole credit for this,

991
01:14:37,600 --> 01:14:39,280
but marketing is doing awesome.

992
01:14:39,280 --> 01:14:40,080
Let's talk to them.

993
01:14:40,080 --> 01:14:41,360
What are they doing?

994
01:14:41,360 --> 01:14:42,800
Why is this going so well?

995
01:14:42,800 --> 01:14:46,480
What have they learned from this that we can work with them more closely?"

996
01:14:46,480 --> 01:14:51,679
If your sector is just doing really well, be like,"Okay, well, what about this is is working right now?

997
01:14:51,679 --> 01:14:53,360
What might change in the future?

998
01:14:53,360 --> 01:14:54,400
How can we understand this?"

999
01:14:54,400 --> 01:15:05,199
So I think the challenge when things are going well is to is to keep that curiosity going and to keep celebrating the things not just that your team is

1000
01:15:05,199 --> 01:15:14,960
doing but that everyone is doing and to take that time where you have a little bit more leeway where there's less pressure on you in the moment to build those connections with other parts of

1001
01:15:14,960 --> 01:15:19,840
the organization to see where that really good work is happening.

1002
01:15:19,840 --> 01:15:29,840
Um, you know, one thing that that makes me sad is when teams look upon each other with envy and disgust,

1003
01:15:29,840 --> 01:15:30,080
right?

1004
01:15:30,080 --> 01:15:35,840
When it's like this team's doing like they're doing great work, but they're not held to the same standards that we are and it's not fair and,

1005
01:15:35,840 --> 01:15:37,600
you know, they're the team that everyone likes.

1006
01:15:37,600 --> 01:15:45,040
It's like go talk to them because there's probably something you can learn from them.

1007
01:15:45,040 --> 01:15:48,960
And if they're the team that's getting positive attention, that's doing meaningful work,

1008
01:15:48,960 --> 01:15:50,560
there's probably a reason for that.

1009
01:15:50,560 --> 01:15:55,040
And if you can understand that reason and you can align your work with that team's work,

1010
01:15:55,040 --> 01:15:57,760
that's probably going to be really good for you.

1011
01:15:57,760 --> 01:16:03,360
So again, I think in a lot of cases, it comes back down to that control thing, right?

1012
01:16:03,360 --> 01:16:12,159
If we can't feel a sense of control over things are going well because we did this, we tend to disconnect ourselves from things going well and say like,

1013
01:16:12,159 --> 01:16:21,280
well, I can't like it almost feels dangerous to engage with it because what if we didn't do anything but good things are still happening.

1014
01:16:21,280 --> 01:16:30,480
And I think just keeping that openness, keeping that curiosity going puts you in a much better position for when things inevitably begin to either plateau or decline,

1015
01:16:30,480 --> 01:16:34,640
which is the cyclical nature of all things.

1016
01:16:34,640 --> 01:16:35,199
Wow.

1017
01:16:35,199 --> 01:16:35,600
Profound.

1018
01:16:35,600 --> 01:16:36,640
There.

1019
01:16:36,640 --> 01:16:46,880
Maybe to start to wrap up our conversation, what's what's maybe one question from the book or even from this conversation that you think product leaders,

1020
01:16:46,880 --> 01:16:53,440
product teams should ask themselves to help them solve problems that maybe they're not seeing and to help their team operate better.

1021
01:16:53,440 --> 01:16:57,520
>> I mean, I I love the would you fund this team if you were the CEO question.

1022
01:16:57,520 --> 01:17:01,120
I know that that can feel a little confrontational sometimes.

1023
01:17:01,120 --> 01:17:10,400
So, a a gentler way of bringing that up is to say, "What's one sentence you'd want to be able to say at the end of this year that would leave you feeling awesome about this team's work?"

1024
01:17:10,400 --> 01:17:14,719
Like, what's something, you know, at the end of the year, everything went really well for this team.

1025
01:17:14,719 --> 01:17:20,560
You run into the CEO in the hallway and you say, "I feel awesome because we did this."

1026
01:17:20,560 --> 01:17:24,880
And and you'll sometimes get very different answers from different people on the team.

1027
01:17:24,880 --> 01:17:28,159
Building on those answers, saying like,"Okay, this is what you care about.

1028
01:17:28,159 --> 01:17:29,199
This is what I care about.

1029
01:17:29,199 --> 01:17:30,640
This is what I'm worried about.

1030
01:17:30,640 --> 01:17:32,880
This is what I'm excited about.

1031
01:17:32,880 --> 01:17:39,760
That's how you get that magical people in a room building together or or musicians in in a room writing their next song.

1032
01:17:39,760 --> 01:17:40,080
Right.

1033
01:17:40,080 --> 01:17:42,239
>> What a call back at the beginning.

1034
01:17:42,239 --> 01:17:51,920
